metadata.name: Traversal #15
metadata.description:
Traversal is the marriage of two simple geometric ideas: a set of somewhat unruly, intersecting diagonal shapes, and a minimally reduced corner perspective that gives them depth.

The depicted bodies are entirely feasible as a 3D scene, and yet this composition is all about illusion. The hatch fill creates a perception of light. The dithering on the faces produces a sense of material texture. The squiggly lines imitate freehand drawing. The spatial perspective itself is achieved through a purely two-dimensional algorithm of polygon intersections and line hiding.

The original medium of my compositions is the pen plotter, and Traversal is no exception. It is entirely vector-based, and can be plotted directly. I use Paper.js to render it on-screen and as SVG.

~

To generate and download a plottable SVG file, press `S`. Please be patient; this process can take a while. The SVG can be plotted on an A5 paper. It contains two layers visible in Inkscape, so you can plot the light grey sketch lines with a different pen, or omit them altogether.

metadata.name: Cuts #18
metadata.description:
Cuts is an abstract representation of the exact moments in our lives when something is cut. It could be moving to a different country, being fired, quitting a bad habit, when a relationship ends or when you receive a very bad (or good!) news.
By themselves, cuts are not positive or negative events; it really depends on who you were before and who you wish to be after. But one thing is sure: every cut creates a new space that wasn’t there. This space could be small or huge, ordered or chaotic, regardless, you have to deal with it. Sometimes cuts try to resist and heal themselves extruding the core of the fibres we are made of, but they will fail. A cut is irreversible and it’s up to us to fill the gap with meaning.

Main features include:
- Curated palettes (21)
- Drawing modes (3)
- Extrusions (yes/no)
- Orientation (3)
- Overlapping (yes/no)
- Covered area (2)
- Cut position (2)

In live mode:
- Press [s] to save a 2400x2400 px image
- Press [t] to toggle shading (sometimes flat colours rock!)
- Press [c] to see copyright notice
- Press [f] to log features in console

By Todemashi 2022
NFT License 2.0

### NOTES
Made with p5js and GLSL shaders.
Shaders are based on tutorials and code by Patricio Gonzalez Vivo - The Book of Shaders - https://thebookofshaders.com/

metadata.name: Other ways #231
metadata.description:
Inspired by Paul Klee’s painting « Highways and byways », « Other ways » propose to build your own and unique generative painting.

7 features, including 4 main styles, 8 color palettes, 5 different parameters of the generative process.


Please note that the preview image is more saturated than the real token due to fxhash GPU management.

In Open Live window, press « s » to save the current image.
To get a High Resolution Image : press « r » to change the resolution for high definition, the image will reload and you can then use « s » to save the image (you can change DP in the URL to  a greater value for an even larger resolution in case you want to print it big).
This project is dimensionless, the Preview and OpenLive images are the same.

This artwork was created using p5js and scribble.

TidallyDisruptedStar. Paris. Jan 2022.

twitter : @TidallyD

metadata.name: Fanfàrria #60
metadata.description:
Fanfàrria (Catalan for fanfare), a musical piece often played by trumpets in local town parties.

A mix of detailed handcrafted watercolor strips drawn in a generative motion that create an illusion of a trail of feathers. The different variations are based on the variance of color in the feathers and the motion of the trail.

Less variance on the feathers is rearer.

metadata.name: Endless Drawing #360
metadata.description:
Generator of virtually infinite drawings based on epicyclic motions. 
 
A polyline of three or more segments rotates around a predefined center, progressively changing its configuration. The center of rotation is located at the top outside the display area. The changes are made by rotating the first segment around the center and subsequent segments around the end vertex of the previous one. The segments from the second onward are drawn at each frame, and all traces are then moved down.

Depending on the lengths of the segments and the individual rotation speeds, the drawings can repeat in the same exact way after a few minutes or after very many years.
 
Antonio Belluscio (@livinbits)
November 2021

Viewing in live mode on smartphones or in portrait format windows is recommended.
With a click or tap, you can increase/decrease the scrolling speed.
